Lars Clausen wrote:

&gt;On Thu, 2004-07-15 at 19:42, stack wrote:
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;&gt;Its possible to disable heritrix&#39;s writing of compressed arcs via 
&gt;&gt;configuration, if its local policy to collect in uncompressed mode.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;On &quot;in-format compression ... confuse people&quot;, I&#39;m with the Tom Emerson 
&gt;&gt;comment that its not zlib thats at fault.
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;I&#39;m not saying that zlib is any worse or better than other compression
&gt;algorithms in comprehensibility.  It&#39;s that if you just get the file,
&gt;it&#39;s binary junk, not the immediately comprehensible ASCII-based ARC
&gt;format that had me convinced would be readable 100 years from now
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;One could argue that the same holds for hardware or file system
&gt;compression, but I would say that in those cases, if you can read the
&gt;files, you get it out of compressed mode.  Only if a tape/disk was found
&gt;so long from now that none of the original hardware is available and
&gt;some kind of other scan is set up would the compression be a problem.
&gt;
&gt;  
&gt;
Zlib&#39;s comprehensibility is not an attribute of interest.  Its that zlib 
is an open and pervasive software technique.  If anything is going to be 
around in 100 years, its likely to be.  In other words, I&#39;d argue, 
gzipped ARC files won&#39;t be &#39;binary junk&#39; in 100 years.  If ARCs are to 
be compressed in a manner thats shareable across repositories, the 
compression should be based a technique that has the open and pervasive 
attributes of zlib.

Should the way the Archive compresses ARCs be added to the ARC 
definition as an addendum (&quot;If file ends in &#39;.gz&#39; or begins with 
GZIP_MAGIC...&quot;) as a description of the common, agreed technique for 
sharing compressed ARCs across repositories?

I see the decision as to whether or not to compress in hardware as a 
local policy decision made by a particular archiving institution though 
it&#39;d probably be wise to try and do it with a hardware that had the same 
open and pervasive attributes as zlib has.

&gt;One way to make compression a little more workable would be to not
&gt;compress the meatdata lines.  That way, there wouldn&#39;t be any confusion
&gt;about the length of the block, and it would be possible to understand
&gt;the structure of the file without using zlib.  It could (and should) be
&gt;indicated in the header what compression style is used.  
&gt;
&gt;  
&gt;
Its an appealing notion but a radical departure; at least for us at the 
Archive.  It&#39;d break all of our repository accessing tools.  If we went 
this path, we should go the whole hog and adopt a permutation on the 
swedish archiving format where they use MIME as technology for 
describing the record that follows.

St.Ack


